{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "NYISO Manual 23 interconnection fees Class Year Interconnection Request fee study deposit SIS FAC SRIS cost responsibility",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "NYISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "772cbe24-0adc-4841-a6aa-8927cd1c6c34",
        "score": 0.58455145,
        "text": "The document page from the New York ISO Installed Capacity Manual outlines procedures related to ICAP Demand Curves and supplemental supply fees:\n\n1. **FERC Filing of ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.7):** \n   - NYISO must file Board-approved ICAP Demand Curve parameters with FERC by November 30 before the first Capability Period in the review. This includes methodologies and inputs for annual updates for the remaining Capability Years.\n\n2. **Annual Updates of the ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.8):**\n   - NYISO will conduct annual updates for years 2-4 of the ICAP Demand Curves as per the NYISO Services Tariff. Results are presented to Market Participants, and updated values are posted by November 30 before the new Capability Year. These updates are accessible online.\n\n3. **Supplemental Supply Fee (5.7):**\n   - If a Load Serving Entity (LSE) fails to meet its capacity requirements after an ICAP Spot Market Auction, a supplemental supply fee is assessed. This fee is based on the Market-Clearing Price of Unforced Capacity. NYISO uses these fees to procure Unforced Capacity at or below the market-clearing price from qualified suppliers. Suppliers include those not previously qualified, those offering above market-clearing prices, and those not offering in the auction.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_229.jpg",
          "page_num": 229,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5729786,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "652b35ce-564f-49a2-96b3-81d35d8aa225",
        "score": 0.57092696,
        "text": "The document outlines requirements for establishing communication between a DSASP Provider and the New York ISO. Key points include:\n\n1. **Communication Configuration**:\n   - Required if the DSASP Provider's total enrollment is \u2264 25 MW.\n   - Involves one communications vendor, a set of network components, and one ICCP node.\n   - The DSASP Provider and NYISO must complete vendor agreements for direct communications.\n\n2. **Hardware and Software Requirements**:\n   - Establish a contract with a communications vendor to link to NYISO.\n   - Select circuit type, bandwidth, and obtain a Virtual Private LAN Service or MPLS.\n   - Identify network hardware, ensuring routers support encryption and firewalls are recommended.\n   - Software must support ICCP communication as both client and server.\n   - Configure hardware/software for ICCP Node, collaborating with NYISO personnel.\n   - Ensure scalability and redundancy, with systems designed for 99.99% availability.\n   - Identify necessary servers and hardware based on software vendor requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_91.jpg",
          "page_num": 91,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f555ba59-0aa3-494c-b50f-fbfc654d4f1f",
        "score": 0.55936015,
        "text": "The document discusses the process and results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) study cycle related to deliverability and transmission planning for energy projects. It outlines the requirements for projects to pay for upgrades to receive Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) and Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) rights. The study identifies necessary upgrades to ensure projects can deliver energy without violating transmission constraints.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The Class Year Study helps developers decide whether to pay for required upgrades, receive ERIS or CRIS rights, or withdraw.\n- Recent studies have taken about two years, with increasing numbers of participants and costs.\n- CY21 began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS.\n- The CY21 SUF Study identified over $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability.\n- Sixteen projects requesting 4 GW of CRIS were not fully deliverable, with less than 400 MW partially deliverable.\n- NYISO identified $1.5 billion in System Deliverability Upgrades (SDUs) for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP.\n- The document includes a table summarizing the results and costs of the CY21 SDU Study.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_46.jpg",
          "page_num": 46,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "d5b29f8d-c4cf-4d57-a755-1f6969f46e53",
        "score": 0.5570167,
        "text": "The document page outlines the annual budget charge and other non-budget charges and payments for services provided by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). It categorizes these charges into three main areas: \n\n1. **Physical Operation of the NY Control Area**\n2. **Administration of NYISO tariffs and related agreements**\n3. **Other Non-Budget Charges**\n\nDetails of these services are found in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the Accounting and Billing Manual.\n\n**Recovery of NYISO Costs**: Information on cost recovery is available in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Payment for Service**: Payment details are also in Rate Schedule 1 of the NYISO OATT and the NYISO Services Tariff.\n\n**Services at the Request of a Market Participant**: Market participants can request and pay for specific NYISO services, including:\n\n- System Reliability Impact Study (ESRIS)\n- Facilities Study\n- Local Control Center operator training\n- Re-enforcement Option Study (also requested by PSC)\n- System Impact Study\n- Interconnection Study",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Manual_2_Ancillary_Services_Manual/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "Manual 2 Ancillary Services Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b164d87f-9ccf-468c-8cb0-176f30fb3261",
        "score": 0.5523375,
        "text": "The document page discusses the requirements for suppliers to provide the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) with documentation of costs related to maintenance activities as defined in the Long-Term Service Agreement (LTSA). It specifies that suppliers can include cost escalators in their submissions if they are part of the LTSA. Suppliers must submit contracts to demonstrate the variability of costs, which are subject to review by NYISO and its Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) for reasonableness and appropriateness. The NYISO allows the inclusion of certain costs, like fuel management fees, in cost-based references when presented on a per mmBTU basis.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_38.jpg",
          "page_num": 38,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ac6d61c9-86f0-4401-96ec-0453922296a1",
        "score": 0.53429127,
        "text": "The document outlines the interconnection process for Distributed Energy Resources (DER) facilities with the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Interconnection is allowed through the NYISO Small Generator Interconnection Procedure (SGIP) or other approved procedures. Interconnection studies must be completed and approved before DER enrollment in the Aggregation System. The process uses interconnection study data to validate DER characteristics. Aggregators must provide additional interconnection information to the Distribution Utility if requested. The focus is on facility-level requirements, not asset-level, and specific requirements apply to resources with energy duration limitations. DER facilities solely comprising Demand Side Resources are exempt from certain interconnection studies. A diagram illustrates the relationship between assets, DER facilities, and aggregation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_23.jpg",
          "page_num": 23,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "11dff9a6-8791-4982-a3f6-76dc13a56690",
        "score": 0.5327079,
        "text": "The document page outlines two data specifications related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO):\n\n1. **NYISO Data Specification (Section 4.3):** This provides Market Participants with a reference document detailing where data requests exist within NYISO's processes. It includes an overview of submitting data to NYISO in line with NERC Standard IRO-010 Requirements and NYISO Tariff provisions. Detailed information is available in the referenced processes or documentation.\n\n2. **New York Local Control Center (LCC) Data Specification (Section 4.4):** This offers New York Transmission Owners, who are also NERC registered Transmission Operators, a reference for submitting data to NYISO according to NERC Standard TOP-003 Requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reliability_Compliance_and_Enforcement_Manual/page_14.jpg",
          "page_num": 14,
          "title": "Reliability Compliance and Enforcement Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8323e708-96b8-4316-aab9-12facaf5c329",
        "score": 0.52938676,
        "text": "The document page outlines the responsibility of informing the ISO (Independent System Operator) about significant changes in the incremental costs associated with a Demand Side Resource's load reduction. It mandates that updated cost information must be submitted to the ISO at least annually. A reference is made to MST Section 23.7.4.2 for further details.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Reference_Level_Manual/page_44.jpg",
          "page_num": 44,
          "title": "Reference Level Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "587e56d4-9014-43f6-9224-6e7af4fccaf6",
        "score": 0.5288018,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for assigning Capacity Accreditation Resource Classes to Installed Capacity Suppliers for the upcoming Capability Year by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Assignment Notification**: NYISO will inform each supplier of their assigned class before the deadline in the ICAP Event Calendar.\n\n2. **Dispute Resolution**: If a supplier believes their assignment is incorrect, they must notify NYISO before the deadline. If unresolved, NYISO will assign a class for the year.\n\n3. **Supplier Responsibilities**: Suppliers must provide their class assignment to NYISO by the deadline.\n\n4. **Audit and Penalties**: NYISO may audit assignments. Inaccurate assignments can lead to penalties.\n\n5. **Finality of Assignments**: Assignments are final after the deadline. Late market entries will receive their class during registration.\n\n6. **Reference**: More details are available on the NYISO accreditation webpage.\n\nThe document emphasizes deadlines, accuracy, and the finality of assignments to ensure proper market operations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_249.jpg",
          "page_num": 249,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

