      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "f555ba59-0aa3-494c-b50f-fbfc654d4f1f",
        "score": 0.6032008,
        "text": "The document discusses the process and results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) study cycle related to deliverability and transmission planning for energy projects. It outlines the requirements for projects to pay for upgrades to receive Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) and Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) rights. The study identifies necessary upgrades to ensure projects can deliver energy without violating transmission constraints.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The Class Year Study helps developers decide whether to pay for required upgrades, receive ERIS or CRIS rights, or withdraw.\n- Recent studies have taken about two years, with increasing numbers of participants and costs.\n- CY21 began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS.\n- The CY21 SUF Study identified over $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability.\n- Sixteen projects requesting 4 GW of CRIS were not fully deliverable, with less than 400 MW partially deliverable.\n- NYISO identified $1.5 billion in System Deliverability Upgrades (SDUs) for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP.\n- The document includes a table summarizing the results and costs of the CY21 SDU Study.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_46.jpg",
          "page_num": 46,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1fe556ac-9444-4fff-be8b-78b250cdcb0c",
        "score": 0.5888813,
        "text": "The document discusses the System Deliverability Upgrade (SDU) Study, which identifies necessary upgrades for resources to meet the New York Independent System Operator\u2019s (NYISO) Deliverability Interconnection Standard. Developers must pay for these upgrades to obtain the right to sell capacity. After a Class Year Study, developers decide whether to pay for upgrades, receive rights, or withdraw. The number of resources and costs in these studies have increased, taking about two years to complete.\n\nThe results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) are detailed. The study began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS. The study identified $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability. Sixteen projects, totaling over 4 GW of CRIS, were not fully deliverable. NYISO identified $1.5 billion in SDUs for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP. These costs are shown over a 20-year period as a percentage of the 2022/23 capacity market net CONE.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_58.jpg",
          "page_num": 58,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5845773,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7e1da819-1e4b-42d9-b76b-7225657a28dc",
        "score": 0.5668761,
        "text": "The document outlines the procedures and requirements for submitting DMNC (Dependable Maximum Net Capability) or DMGC (Dependable Maximum Generating Capacity) test data or data from actual operations to the New York ISO (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Submission Requirements**: Failure to submit the required data or a completed supplemental form may result in financial penalties.\n\n2. **Purpose**: The data is used to establish a generating resource's Installed Capacity value, which is adjusted according to specific sections of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Validation Process**: Submitted data must be complete and in an acceptable format. NYISO will validate and approve or reject the data within 30 days.\n\n4. **Discrepancies**: Any discrepancies between submitted data and NYISO billing information must be resolved through an audit process within the 30-day period.\n\n5. **Approval and Rejection**: If approved, the data is valid for the current Capability Period. If rejected, the supplier can resubmit data, accept NYISO's determined value, or request an audit.\n\n6. **Audit Process**: If an audit is requested, NYISO will work with the supplier. If the audit supports the supplier's data, the original rating remains. If not, the supplier must resubmit data, and deficiency charges may apply.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_85.jpg",
          "page_num": 85,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ac6d61c9-86f0-4401-96ec-0453922296a1",
        "score": 0.5647614,
        "text": "The document outlines the interconnection process for Distributed Energy Resources (DER) facilities with the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Interconnection is allowed through the NYISO Small Generator Interconnection Procedure (SGIP) or other approved procedures. Interconnection studies must be completed and approved before DER enrollment in the Aggregation System. The process uses interconnection study data to validate DER characteristics. Aggregators must provide additional interconnection information to the Distribution Utility if requested. The focus is on facility-level requirements, not asset-level, and specific requirements apply to resources with energy duration limitations. DER facilities solely comprising Demand Side Resources are exempt from certain interconnection studies. A diagram illustrates the relationship between assets, DER facilities, and aggregation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_23.jpg",
          "page_num": 23,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "772cbe24-0adc-4841-a6aa-8927cd1c6c34",
        "score": 0.55771124,
        "text": "The document page from the New York ISO Installed Capacity Manual outlines procedures related to ICAP Demand Curves and supplemental supply fees:\n\n1. **FERC Filing of ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.7):** \n   - NYISO must file Board-approved ICAP Demand Curve parameters with FERC by November 30 before the first Capability Period in the review. This includes methodologies and inputs for annual updates for the remaining Capability Years.\n\n2. **Annual Updates of the ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.8):**\n   - NYISO will conduct annual updates for years 2-4 of the ICAP Demand Curves as per the NYISO Services Tariff. Results are presented to Market Participants, and updated values are posted by November 30 before the new Capability Year. These updates are accessible online.\n\n3. **Supplemental Supply Fee (5.7):**\n   - If a Load Serving Entity (LSE) fails to meet its capacity requirements after an ICAP Spot Market Auction, a supplemental supply fee is assessed. This fee is based on the Market-Clearing Price of Unforced Capacity. NYISO uses these fees to procure Unforced Capacity at or below the market-clearing price from qualified suppliers. Suppliers include those not previously qualified, those offering above market-clearing prices, and those not offering in the auction.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_229.jpg",
          "page_num": 229,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ef466c90-4b42-4bca-88af-e67fc550132d",
        "score": 0.5559366,
        "text": "The document discusses the NYISO's approach to managing guarantee payment uplift charges, which are additional payments to market participants not covered by LBMP and other revenues. These charges are challenging to hedge and can obscure economic signals. The document emphasizes minimizing these charges to ensure efficient market operations.\n\nIn 2021, guarantee payment uplifts totaled $54 million, a 28% increase from 2020, mainly due to higher gas prices affecting gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $26 million of these charges, with a significant portion paid to generators committed for local reliability needs. Recommendations include modeling local reserve requirements to reduce these uplifts and improve price transparency.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_78.jpg",
          "page_num": 78,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "04cacb03-0c99-49a9-b86d-593a314bdadd",
        "score": 0.55314493,
        "text": "The document page contains two bar graphs related to uplift costs from guarantee payments for the years 2021 and 2022.\n\n1. **Figure A-111: Uplift Costs from Guarantee Payments by Month (2021-2022)**\n   - This graph shows monthly uplift costs categorized by different types of payments: Day Ahead Local, DAMAP Local, Min Oil Burn, Day Ahead Statewide, Real Time Local, DAMAP Statewide, Real Time Statewide, and EDRP/SCR.\n   - The costs are displayed in millions of dollars, with a comparison between 2021 and 2022.\n   - The total costs for 2022 are $94 million, while for 2021, they are $54 million.\n\n2. **Figure A-112: Uplift Costs from Guarantee Payments by Region (2021-2022)**\n   - This graph presents uplift costs by region: New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, Imports, and EDRP/SCR.\n   - The costs are broken down quarterly for each region.\n   - The total costs for 2022 are $94 million, compared to $54 million in 2021.\n   - New York City and Long Island have the highest costs in both years.\n\nBoth graphs illustrate an increase in uplift costs from 2021 to 2022, with detailed breakdowns by category and region.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_343.jpg",
          "page_num": 343,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e089bbbb-5055-4704-b25f-a4be697a8fb6",
        "score": 0.5521331,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the New York ISO Capacity Market, focusing on bid submissions and payment processes for Unforced Capacity.\n\n1. **Bid Submission:**\n   - Timely submission of a Bid Package does not guarantee inclusion in an auction.\n   - The Bid Package must comply with the ISO Services Tariff and ICAP Manual.\n   - NYISO can reject incomplete or insufficient Electronic Bids.\n   - If a Bidder's Agreement is rejected, they can submit a replacement during the Bidding Period.\n   - Bidders are responsible for submitting correct and complete Bid Packages.\n   - Bidders cannot assign rights or obligations under a Bid Package without proper representation and warranties.\n\n2. **Payment Procedures for Unforced Capacity:**\n   - Bidders must pay for Unforced Capacity after auction results are posted.\n   - The Award Notice specifies the amount and details of the Unforced Capacity.\n   - Payments for Strip Auctions are settled monthly, with bills issued for one-sixth of the Total Purchase Price.\n   - Payments for Monthly and Spot Market Auctions are also settled monthly, net of any rebates.\n   - By 10:00 AM on the first banking day after the fifteenth day of the month, Bidders must wire funds equal to the cumulative Total Purchase Price from all auctions as per the monthly billing invoice.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_13.jpg",
          "page_num": 13,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ecdb3f8-11f2-4f49-a085-e78469e5814c",
        "score": 0.55144197,
        "text": "The document discusses \"Guarantee Payment Uplift Charges\" in the New York electricity market. These charges are used to recover additional payments not covered by Locational Based Marginal Prices (LBMPs) and other revenues. The charges are difficult to hedge and lack transparency, so minimizing them is crucial for efficient market operation.\n\nIn 2022, the total guarantee payment uplift was $94 million, a 74% increase from 2021, primarily due to higher gas prices and increased commitment costs for gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $50 million, or 53% of the total uplift, marking a 92% increase from 2021. A significant portion, over $36 million, was paid to generators committed for local reliability requirements. The document includes a figure showing uplift costs by region and category for 2021 and 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_102.jpg",
          "page_num": 102,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

