      {
        "id": "e089bbbb-5055-4704-b25f-a4be697a8fb6",
        "score": 0.5521331,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the New York ISO Capacity Market, focusing on bid submissions and payment processes for Unforced Capacity.\n\n1. **Bid Submission:**\n   - Timely submission of a Bid Package does not guarantee inclusion in an auction.\n   - The Bid Package must comply with the ISO Services Tariff and ICAP Manual.\n   - NYISO can reject incomplete or insufficient Electronic Bids.\n   - If a Bidder's Agreement is rejected, they can submit a replacement during the Bidding Period.\n   - Bidders are responsible for submitting correct and complete Bid Packages.\n   - Bidders cannot assign rights or obligations under a Bid Package without proper representation and warranties.\n\n2. **Payment Procedures for Unforced Capacity:**\n   - Bidders must pay for Unforced Capacity after auction results are posted.\n   - The Award Notice specifies the amount and details of the Unforced Capacity.\n   - Payments for Strip Auctions are settled monthly, with bills issued for one-sixth of the Total Purchase Price.\n   - Payments for Monthly and Spot Market Auctions are also settled monthly, net of any rebates.\n   - By 10:00 AM on the first banking day after the fifteenth day of the month, Bidders must wire funds equal to the cumulative Total Purchase Price from all auctions as per the monthly billing invoice.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual_Attachments/page_13.jpg",
          "page_num": 13,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual Attachments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8ecdb3f8-11f2-4f49-a085-e78469e5814c",
        "score": 0.55144197,
        "text": "The document discusses \"Guarantee Payment Uplift Charges\" in the New York electricity market. These charges are used to recover additional payments not covered by Locational Based Marginal Prices (LBMPs) and other revenues. The charges are difficult to hedge and lack transparency, so minimizing them is crucial for efficient market operation.\n\nIn 2022, the total guarantee payment uplift was $94 million, a 74% increase from 2021, primarily due to higher gas prices and increased commitment costs for gas-fired units. New York City accounted for $50 million, or 53% of the total uplift, marking a 92% increase from 2021. A significant portion, over $36 million, was paid to generators committed for local reliability requirements. The document includes a figure showing uplift costs by region and category for 2021 and 2022.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2022/page_102.jpg",
          "page_num": 102,
          "title": "2022 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

